Time Complexity is a way to measure how fast an algorithm runs as the input size grows.

Instead of counting exact seconds (which depend on your machine), we focus on how the number of operations increases with input size n.

🔹 Simple Idea

If you have an input of size n, time complexity tells you:

“How does the runtime grow when n becomes large?”



| Complexity     | Meaning                             | Example                    |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| **O(1)**       | Constant time (doesn’t depend on n) | Accessing an array element |
| **O(log n)**   | Logarithmic (very fast growth)      | Binary search              |
| **O(n)**       | Linear                              | Loop through array         |
| **O(n log n)** | Efficient sorting                   | Merge sort                 |
| **O(n²)**      | Quadratic (slow for large n)        | Nested loops               |
| **O(2ⁿ)**      | Exponential (very slow)             | Recursive brute force      |
